1. Plot most popular domains¶

In [4]:
link_regex = r"https?://(:?www\.|)(.*?)(/|\")|\"-\""

counts = (
    lines.filter(lambda l: "semicomplete.com" not in l)
    .map(lambda l: (re.search(link_regex, l).group(2), 1))
    .filter(lambda x: x[0])
    .reduceByKey(lambda a, b: a + b)
    .takeOrdered(8, lambda x: -x[1])
)

plt.barh([c[0] for c in reversed(counts)], [c[1] for c in reversed(counts)])
plt.show()

2. Most requested images¶

In [5]:
file_regex = '"GET (\S+/|)(\S+\.png|jpg) '


def get_file_name(line):
    file_type = re.search(file_regex, line)
    return (file_type.group(2), 1) if file_type else ("", 0)


file_counts = (
    lines.filter(lambda l: "GET" in l)
    .map(lambda l: get_file_name(l))
    .reduceByKey(lambda a, b: a + b)
    .filter(lambda x: x[1] > 0)
    .takeOrdered(20, lambda x: -x[1])
)
In [6]:
xs = [file for file, _ in reversed(file_counts)]
ys = [count for _, count in reversed(file_counts)]

plt.barh(xs, ys)
plt.title("Resource type counts")
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

3. Plot request per minute frequency¶

In [7]:
minute_regex = "\[\d+/\w+/\d+:(\d+):(\d+)"


def get_time(line):
    return re.search(minute_regex, line).group(1, 2), 1


requests_counts = (
    lines.map(lambda l: get_time(l)).reduceByKey(lambda a, b: a + b).collect()
)

requests_counts = sorted(requests_counts, key=lambda x: x[0])

# The only collected logs are from the 5th minute of each hour
In [8]:
labels = [f"{hour}:{minute}" for (hour, minute), _ in requests_counts]
counts = [count for _, count in requests_counts]

plt.figure(figsize=(7, 5))
plt.plot(labels, counts, marker="o")

plt.xticks(rotation=90)

plt.xlabel("Time")
plt.ylabel("Count")
plt.title("Counts over Time")

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

4. Piechart of operating systems¶

In [9]:
os_regex = "Macintosh|Windows|Linux|iPhone"


def get_os(line):
    os_name = re.search(os_regex, line)
    return (os_name.group(), 1) if os_name else ("other logs", 1)


os_counts = lines.map(lambda l: get_os(l)).reduceByKey(lambda a, b: a + b)

name_counts = os_counts.collect()
In [10]:
names = [c[0] for c in name_counts]
counts = [c[1] for c in name_counts]

for i, n in enumerate(names):
    if n == "iPhone":
        names[i] = "iOS"

plt.pie(counts, labels=names)
plt.show()

In [12]:
# using user_agent package


def is_bot(line):
    user_agent_string = line
    user_agent = parse(line)
    return user_agent.is_bot


bot_count = lines.filter(is_bot).count()

bot_ratio = bot_count / lines.count()
bot_ratio
Out[12]:
0.1089

Detecting most popular bots has more positives than using a package

It's highly doubtful that the first approach yields false positives so we can assume it's a better way of detecting bots

In [13]:
ip_regex = "[(\d\.)]+"

ips = lines.map(lambda l: re.match(ip_regex, l).group(0)).distinct()
In [14]:
def get_lat_long(ip):
    try:
        res = DbIpCity.get(ip, api_key="free")
    except Exception as e:
        return None, None
    return res.latitude, res.longitude


# coords = [get_lat_long(ip) for ip in ips.collect()]
coords = ips.map(get_lat_long).collect()

coords = [(float(lat), float(long)) for lat, long in coords if lat != None]
coords[:5]
